SIMPLE: wet
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wet
<hw>Wet</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Wetter</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Wettest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wet</ets>, <ets>weet</ets>, AS. <ets>w⟦aemac⟧t</ets>; akin to
OFries. <ets>w⟦emac⟧t</ets>, Icel. <ets>v⟦amac⟧tr</ets>, Sw.
<ets>v⟦aring⟧t</ets>, Dan. <ets>vaad</ets>, and E. <ets>water</ets>.
⟦root⟧137. See <er>Water</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Containing, or consisting of, water or other liquid;
moist; soaked with a liquid; having water or other liquid upon the
surface; <as>as, <ex>wet</ex> land; a <ex>wet</ex> cloth; a <ex>wet</ex>
table.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wet</xex> cheeks.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Very damp; rainy; <as>as, <ex>wet</ex> weather; a
<ex>wet</ex> season</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wet</xex> October's torrent
flood.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Employing, or done by means of,
water or some other liquid; <as>as, the <ex>wet</ex> extraction of
copper, in distinction from <ex>dry</ex> extraction in which dry heat or
fusion is employed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Refreshed with liquor; drunk.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Wet blanket</b></col>, <col><b>Wet
dock</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Blanket</er>,
<er>Dock</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Wet goods</b></col>,
<cd>intoxicating liquors.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Nasty; humid; damp; moist. See
<er>Nasty</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wet
<hw>Wet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>w⟦aemac⟧ta</ets>. See <er>Wet</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Water or wetness; moisture or humidity in
considerable degree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have here a cloth and wipe away the <qex>wet</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now the sun, with more effectual beams,⟦br⟧
Had cheered the face of earth, and dried the <qex>wet</qex>⟦br⟧
From drooping plant.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rainy weather; foggy or misty weather.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A dram; a drink.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wet
<hw>Wet</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wet</conjf> (rarely <conjf>Wetted</conjf>); <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Wetting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>w⟦aemac⟧tan</ets>.]</ety> <def>To fill or moisten with water or
other liquid; to sprinkle; to cause to have water or other fluid
adherent to the surface; to dip or soak in a liquid; <as>as, to
<ex>wet</ex> a sponge; to <ex>wet</ex> the hands; to <ex>wet</ex>
cloth.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧[The scene] did draw tears from me and
<xex>wetted</xex> my paper.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye mists and exhalations, that now rise . . . ⟦br⟧
Whether to deck with clouds the uncolored sky,⟦br⟧
Or <qex>wet</qex> the thirsty earth with falling showers.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To wet one's whistle</b></col>, <cd>to moisten one's
throat; to drink a dram of liquor.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us drink the other cup <qex>to wet our whistles</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Walton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>wetback</ent>⟦br⟧
